WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.960
Hello everyone, welcome to The Data Scientist Show.

00:00:02.960 --> 00:00:05.400
Today we have Julia Silge.

00:00:05.400 --> 00:00:08.280
Julia is a data scientist and engineering manager

00:00:08.280 --> 00:00:12.040
at PositPBC, formerly known as RStudio,

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:14.760
where she leads a team of developers

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:17.760
building fluent, cohesive, open-source software

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:19.959
for machine learning and MLOps.

00:00:19.959 --> 00:00:23.280
Before Posit, she finished a PhD in astrophysics,

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:26.520
worked for several years in the non-profit space

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:29.559
and was a data scientist at Stack Overflow,

00:00:29.559 --> 00:00:31.320
where some of her most public work

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:34.119
involved the annual developer survey.

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:36.919
Today we'll talk about MLOps tools,

00:00:36.919 --> 00:00:40.240
challenges in survey data, text analysis

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:43.799
and balancing her interest in data science and engineering.

00:00:43.799 --> 00:00:46.040
If you like the show, subscribe to the channel,

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:48.560
leave a comment and give me a five-star review.

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:50.080
Welcome to the show, Julia.

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:51.320
Thank you for having me.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:52.840
I'm really glad to be here.

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:55.880
So Julia, how did you get into data science?

00:00:55.880 --> 00:00:58.680
Great, like you mentioned, my academic background

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:00.959
is in physics and astronomy,

00:01:00.959 --> 00:01:02.880
and I was working in research

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:06.040
and was realizing that the academic world

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:08.279
was not gonna be where it was for me,

00:01:08.279 --> 00:01:10.040
not as fit for the long-term.

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:12.639
My path at that point was a bit circuitous.

00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:15.320
I worked for an ed-tech startup.

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:17.680
I actually was a stay-at-home mom for a few years,

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:21.239
but eventually I started to see some people

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:23.080
who were similar to me in background,

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:24.400
like with this physics and astronomy,

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:27.959
kind of making a transition into data science.

00:01:27.959 --> 00:01:31.199
And I thought, I wondered, I talked to them

00:01:31.199 --> 00:01:32.639
and I was like, wait a minute.

00:01:32.639 --> 00:01:37.440
So there's a job out there where what I do is make plots,

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.879
talk to people about analytical results, analyze data,

00:01:40.879 --> 00:01:42.080
and that's your actual job.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:46.000
That was my favorite part of when I was doing astronomy.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.480
So I thought this is gonna be a pretty good fit for me,

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:53.839
and I decided to try to make this transition.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:56.440
I, at the time, was a little bit underemployed.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:00.120
I actually had been laid off just a few months before this,

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:02.599
and I was employed as a contractor,

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:04.639
and I took about six months,

00:02:04.639 --> 00:02:09.119
and I took basically every MOOC that exists,

00:02:09.119 --> 00:02:11.720
every massive online course that exists

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:15.639
to really learn some of the modern data science languages.

00:02:15.639 --> 00:02:19.479
I had a pretty strong background and programming background

00:02:19.479 --> 00:02:21.360
from the work in physics and astronomy,

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:26.360
but I had never taken any formal stats course.

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:29.479
I didn't know modern data science languages

00:02:29.479 --> 00:02:31.759
like Python, SQL, R.

00:02:31.759 --> 00:02:33.720
I didn't have machine learning experience

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:36.559
because when I came up through physics and astronomy,

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:38.320
it was not as common for people to use

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:40.839
those kinds of machine learning tools.

00:02:40.839 --> 00:02:44.479
I took a bit of time to do a lot of self-study,

00:02:44.479 --> 00:02:47.559
and then as part of that sort of self-study

00:02:47.559 --> 00:02:52.119
to try to make this transition, I started writing a blog.

00:02:52.119 --> 00:02:56.000
And my vision for this blog was that it would be projects

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:00.559
that I could talk to people about during, say, interviews

00:03:00.559 --> 00:03:02.800
or for jobs, like job interviews,

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:05.199
because my resume looked a little weird,

00:03:05.199 --> 00:03:08.800
and I thought I really need to have evidence

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:11.880
that I can do this job, like evidence that I can do this job.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:15.240
It turned out that blogging opened huge doors for me,

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:16.720
both in terms of jobs,

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:19.440
but also with open source collaboration.

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:21.960
I met people that I eventually wrote books with.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:24.759
It really was a big part of my transition

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:27.559
was doing this public-facing kind of work.

00:03:27.559 --> 00:03:29.720
I did get a job.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:33.240
So the first job that I got was in the nonprofit space,

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:35.679
which I think is a really interesting way

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:37.600
for people who are transitioning in,

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:41.800
because often nonprofits have quite a lot of data,

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:44.320
but they don't have as many resources

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:46.800
for how to best use that data,

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:48.839
how to best take advantage of that.

00:03:48.839 --> 00:03:51.759
Of course, salaries are not high in the nonprofit space,

00:03:51.759 --> 00:03:54.360
but it was really a great place for me

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:57.320
to get that first data science title,

00:03:57.320 --> 00:03:59.160
that first job where that was my title,

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:02.279
and to demonstrate that I could do this in a real org.

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:04.119
So that's a little bit of how I got

00:04:04.119 --> 00:04:06.080
to that first kind of data science role.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:09.279
After that, I worked as a data science practitioner,

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:11.199
like with the title data scientist,

00:04:11.199 --> 00:04:13.520
for several years at different kinds of orgs,

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:16.959
moved from the nonprofit space into tech itself,

00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:21.959
and then moved to Posit about four years ago now.

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:23.679
Oh, nice.

00:04:23.679 --> 00:04:26.160
I definitely want to ask more about your blogs,

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:30.279
and that's a great story to use as evidence to get jobs,

00:04:30.279 --> 00:04:33.640
and I also used to write a blog on Medium.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:36.119
It's really fun, and you can turn that

00:04:36.119 --> 00:04:39.200
into so many different type of formats,

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:42.600
and people reach out to you for collaboration,

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:45.040
and you would never imagine those opportunities

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:47.079
if you don't put yourself out there.

00:04:47.079 --> 00:04:49.440
So previously you were data scientist,

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:51.880
now you are a engineering manager,

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:53.480
and you're building machine learning tools,

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:56.880
so how does that transition look like,

00:04:56.880 --> 00:04:59.279
and maybe also tell us what are you working on?

00:04:59.279 --> 00:05:02.600
So when my title was data scientist,

00:05:02.600 --> 00:05:05.279
I noticed that I would spend about 80%

00:05:05.279 --> 00:05:08.160
of my time doing data analysis,

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:11.399
and I would spend about 20% of my time building tools.

00:05:11.399 --> 00:05:15.119
This could be like an internal tool at the organization

00:05:15.119 --> 00:05:18.959
where I was, like an internal package or library,

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:21.320
or something to make the other people

00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:23.079
in my org more effective.

00:05:23.079 --> 00:05:25.399
It also was open source tools.

00:05:25.399 --> 00:05:27.519
I contributed to open source software.

00:05:27.519 --> 00:05:29.079
I started pretty early, actually,

00:05:29.079 --> 00:05:31.200
in my transition into data science,

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:34.320
and I noticed that I really am motivated

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:37.720
by thinking about the systems people use

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:40.480
to get their work done, the tools,

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:44.239
like people's really practical,

00:05:44.239 --> 00:05:46.679
the nitty gritty of how do people do their jobs,

00:05:46.679 --> 00:05:48.679
like how do people do their jobs,

00:05:49.399 --> 00:05:52.200
and I was always interested in kind of that systems thinking

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:55.279
like how do we go about making people more effective

00:05:55.279 --> 00:05:57.320
when they're doing text analysis,

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:59.359
when they're building a machine learning model.

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:03.559
I was happy then, because I got to do data analysis,

00:06:03.559 --> 00:06:07.000
and then kind of 80-20 data analysis tool building.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.359
When I was kind of at a transition point

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:10.920
looking for my next thing,

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:14.000
I was really excited to see this job at Posit,

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:15.600
but I knew it would be a change.

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:16.679
I knew it would be a change,

00:06:16.679 --> 00:06:19.760
because basically it's that flipped.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:23.000
So now I would say I spend 80% of my time

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:27.239
focused on tools for people who are doing data science,

00:06:27.239 --> 00:06:28.760
and maybe 20% of my time

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:31.760
now actually doing data analysis itself.

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:33.359
One thing I notice about myself

00:06:33.359 --> 00:06:37.640
is that I do like to be involved in both.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.720
I really do like to be involved in both.

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:41.040
I think if I ever had a job

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:43.519
that was all one or all the other,

00:06:43.519 --> 00:06:44.839
I would not like that as much.

00:06:44.839 --> 00:06:47.399
It's been interesting to step back

00:06:47.399 --> 00:06:51.200
from a role where my primary role

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:54.679
is doing data analysis or data science

00:06:54.679 --> 00:06:57.239
into a role where my primary focus

00:06:57.239 --> 00:07:01.640
is how can we build effective, fluent tools

00:07:01.640 --> 00:07:05.679
for people to be able to do the kind of tasks that they do.

00:07:05.679 --> 00:07:07.720
So I like doing a little bit of both,

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:11.079
and then now, so I started out when I joined Posit

00:07:11.119 --> 00:07:14.959
just focusing on tools for model development,

00:07:14.959 --> 00:07:16.920
like building machine learning models,

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:19.959
and then transitioned into a leadership role

00:07:19.959 --> 00:07:24.679
and building tools for machine learning operations,

00:07:24.679 --> 00:07:25.839
what people call MLOps.

00:07:25.839 --> 00:07:29.079
So kind of that process of you've already trained a model,

00:07:29.079 --> 00:07:29.959
now what do you do?

00:07:29.959 --> 00:07:33.040
Like, congrats, you trained a model.

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:34.119
What are you gonna do now?

00:07:34.119 --> 00:07:35.880
Like, how do you deploy that model?

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:37.440
How do you version that model?

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:39.600
How do you maintain that model in the long run?

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:41.480
And know when it's time to retrain it.

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:42.679
So that's the kind of work I do now,

00:07:42.679 --> 00:07:45.040
which has been, it's a really interesting space.

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:47.839
And like I said, I love thinking about

00:07:47.839 --> 00:07:50.959
the really practical parts of how people do their jobs,

00:07:50.959 --> 00:07:53.399
and that I get to think about that a lot now.

00:07:53.399 --> 00:07:58.399
Yeah, and for people who are mostly familiar with RStudio,

00:07:58.519 --> 00:08:00.119
the MLOps tool you're building

00:08:00.119 --> 00:08:02.640
is available in both R and Python.

00:08:02.640 --> 00:08:03.480
Yeah, that's right.

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:05.959
So when I joined the company I'm at now,

00:08:05.959 --> 00:08:07.600
it was called RStudio.

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:10.880
And a couple years ago, the company rebranded.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:14.079
So the new name of it is Posit, PositPBC.

00:08:14.079 --> 00:08:16.160
We're a public benefit corporation.

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:20.600
And part of that rebranding was to clarify

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:23.239
that we're not a company that just makes tools for R.

00:08:23.239 --> 00:08:25.119
We're like a data science company.

00:08:25.119 --> 00:08:28.359
So we have tools, the two main languages that we support

00:08:28.359 --> 00:08:32.359
are Python and R, but also some Julia, Observable.

00:08:32.359 --> 00:08:36.479
Basically, tools that people use to deal with data.

00:08:36.479 --> 00:08:37.719
What are the languages?

00:08:37.719 --> 00:08:40.559
The name change, the rebranding,

00:08:40.559 --> 00:08:41.919
in some ways is bittersweet,

00:08:41.919 --> 00:08:45.119
because many people have such positive associations

00:08:45.119 --> 00:08:47.239
with RStudio.

00:08:47.239 --> 00:08:49.599
So it's bittersweet, but I think really important,

00:08:49.599 --> 00:08:53.359
because it more clearly communicates

00:08:53.359 --> 00:08:54.960
the kind of work that we do.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:58.960
So the project that I work on now, it's called Vetiver.

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:03.520
And if you are like a perfume person or a candle person,

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:05.200
you may have heard that word, Vetiver.

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:08.679
So it's a stabilizing ingredient in perfumery.

00:09:08.679 --> 00:09:12.000
So the idea is like in a perfume,

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:13.719
you might have like very,

00:09:13.719 --> 00:09:16.200
lots of volatile kind of fragrances,

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:18.919
but Vetiver is one that's a stabilizing ingredient.

00:09:18.919 --> 00:09:22.080
And so the metaphor here is that Vetiver, the project,

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:24.679
is for stabilizing your models.

00:09:24.679 --> 00:09:26.799
For making your models might be these more,

00:09:26.799 --> 00:09:29.080
these more volatile things,

00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:31.919
but Vetiver helps you have confidence

00:09:31.919 --> 00:09:33.640
in the reliability of the model.

00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:35.919
So it's a project for Python and for R.

00:09:35.919 --> 00:09:39.440
And what it focuses on is you have a model trained

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:43.280
and what do you need to do to maintain it in production,

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:44.679
reliably and efficiently.

00:09:44.679 --> 00:09:47.000
So the three main sort of tasks and approach

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:48.760
are versioning your model.

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:52.559
So that's, oh, I trained it this week and I got this result,

00:09:52.559 --> 00:09:54.440
but I trained it last week and I got these results.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:57.159
Like how do I reliably know where,

00:09:57.159 --> 00:09:59.919
or keep those models versions really organized

00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:01.119
in like a model registry.

00:10:01.119 --> 00:10:02.919
So versioning is the first one.

00:10:02.919 --> 00:10:04.520
The second one is deploying.

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:06.799
So that's that process of getting the model

00:10:06.799 --> 00:10:11.119
out of the computational environment where you developed it.

00:10:11.119 --> 00:10:12.919
Maybe think of that as like your laptop,

00:10:12.919 --> 00:10:14.520
or maybe you might have developed it

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:16.200
in like a server kind of environment,

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:17.760
but you developed it somewhere

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:19.960
and then you need to lift it out

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:23.440
with all the like computational pieces that it needs

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:25.119
and you put it somewhere else

00:10:25.119 --> 00:10:27.599
so that it can be in a production environment

00:10:27.599 --> 00:10:31.799
where it's integrated into the infrastructure of your org.

00:10:31.799 --> 00:10:36.080
So picture that as like one way

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:37.840
that you can do that is with Docker.

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:39.960
There are other ways as well that Vetiver supports,

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:42.400
but that might be a good way to think of it.

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:44.960
So instead of it's on my laptop,

00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:47.479
you're like, ah, it's in a Docker container

00:10:47.479 --> 00:10:49.359
and is ready to make predictions

00:10:49.359 --> 00:10:52.919
because we have captured all the software requirements.

00:10:52.919 --> 00:10:54.679
So versioning is the first piece.

00:10:54.679 --> 00:10:56.559
So think of like a model registry.

00:10:56.559 --> 00:10:58.000
Deploying is the second piece.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.320
So think about getting it off your laptop,

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:02.039
maybe like into a Docker container.

00:11:02.039 --> 00:11:05.039
And then the last piece is model monitoring.

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:07.440
So this is, the model is in production.

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:11.400
It's serving predictions in whatever is appropriate

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:12.760
for your organization.

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:14.880
And the, but you need to know,

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.880
is the model performing as you expect it to?

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:21.320
Is, do you, is it starting to degrade?

00:11:21.320 --> 00:11:24.359
Is it starting, are you having that sort of model drift

00:11:24.359 --> 00:11:25.919
so that you need to address it?

00:11:25.919 --> 00:11:29.840
So that third piece is the monitoring and maintenance piece.

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.080
So it's pretty interesting to work on it

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:35.479
because it is, it's a space where

00:11:35.479 --> 00:11:39.159
there's a lot of uncertainty about what are the approach,

00:11:39.159 --> 00:11:40.919
what are the approaches that are important

00:11:40.919 --> 00:11:43.440
and what are the concerns that people have?

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:44.719
And so it's been really interesting

00:11:44.719 --> 00:11:47.200
to be able to work on these tools,

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:50.799
learn how to make, for example, like how can I make it,

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:55.280
how can my team make it just as easy as possible

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:57.640
for someone to put their model in a Docker container?

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:00.200
Even someone who maybe isn't quite used to Docker yet,

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:02.719
like how can we make it as easy as possible

00:12:02.719 --> 00:12:05.080
for them to take that next step?

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:08.520
Yeah, I like the perfume metaphor.

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:10.080
By the way, you smell great, Julia.

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:11.159
Thank you.

00:12:11.159 --> 00:12:13.080
Part of the reason why this ended up with the name

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:15.400
is because I am actually into perfume

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.119
and candles and stuff like that.

00:12:17.119 --> 00:12:18.880
So I love the metaphor, but thank you.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:20.200
Thank you so much.

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:23.799
Yeah, when you say you want to make this tool easy

00:12:23.799 --> 00:12:27.599
for people who say even they're just new to Docker,

00:12:28.559 --> 00:12:30.000
so how do you connect with a user

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.760
to identify their struggles?

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:36.200
Do you like interview them or do you read some surveys?

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:39.080
Yeah, so before we started deciding

00:12:39.080 --> 00:12:41.000
exactly what would be the shape

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.320
of the MLOps tool we would build,

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:46.200
I did a round of user interviews.

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:50.200
I went to both people who were customers of Posit,

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:53.159
so these are people who use our professional products,

00:12:53.159 --> 00:12:56.520
and also people in the open source ecosystem,

00:12:56.520 --> 00:13:00.000
people who maybe are users of Scikit-learn

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
and our tidy models, or people who are more,

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:04.080
who are not our customers.

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:06.039
So I did rounds of user interviews

00:13:06.039 --> 00:13:08.919
and I had an organized, like I designed an interview

00:13:08.919 --> 00:13:10.799
so that we could really understand

00:13:10.799 --> 00:13:13.760
what do people like about the tools

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:14.919
they're trying to use now?

00:13:14.919 --> 00:13:17.000
What are the deficits that exist?

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.239
For the kind of people who we know

00:13:21.239 --> 00:13:24.799
are our kind of core user persona,

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:26.799
what do they need, what do they need?

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:28.799
I also did quite a bit of reading, actually.

00:13:28.799 --> 00:13:31.119
There's some really interesting,

00:13:31.119 --> 00:13:34.599
a growing body of interesting research

00:13:34.599 --> 00:13:36.760
on MLOps and what it is.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:40.440
There's a couple really great books that came out recently.

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:42.599
Chip Wynn's book is one that's so good.

00:13:42.599 --> 00:13:45.599
Some really interesting papers.

00:13:45.599 --> 00:13:48.840
There's one that was like an interview study

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:50.960
and published like what is MLOps

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:52.359
and how is it different

00:13:52.359 --> 00:13:54.840
from maybe regular software engineering?

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:56.599
So those were the kind of things

00:13:56.599 --> 00:13:59.320
that I used to decide what to build,

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:01.280
would be the nature of what to build.

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:02.919
Can you give us some example?

00:14:02.919 --> 00:14:05.799
What are some common challenges people face

00:14:05.799 --> 00:14:07.719
or you mentioned how is it different

00:14:07.719 --> 00:14:10.520
from regular software engineer or DevOps?

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:12.520
Yeah, one thing that I feel like

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:15.080
was just hammered home to me,

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:16.799
both through my own interviews

00:14:16.799 --> 00:14:18.599
and through the reading that I did,

00:14:18.599 --> 00:14:20.320
in many organizations,

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:25.080
the people who are responsible for this

00:14:25.080 --> 00:14:28.520
are the people who are also developing the model.

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:30.200
So in many places,

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:32.679
if you're someone who develops a model,

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:33.960
and by that I mean that process

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:36.039
of hyperparameter tuning, evaluation,

00:14:36.039 --> 00:14:37.719
like how do I train the model?

00:14:37.719 --> 00:14:41.440
They are often the people who also are responsible

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:44.039
for operationalizing that model.

00:14:44.039 --> 00:14:47.760
But many of the tools that are out there for MLOps

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:52.400
are really built with a software engineer user in mind,

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:55.520
and don't so much really acknowledge

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:58.840
the iterative exploratory nature

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:00.559
of what data science is like,

00:15:00.559 --> 00:15:02.000
what machine learning is like.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.320
The paper, we can add it to your show notes,

00:15:04.320 --> 00:15:07.000
I think that was one of the big takeaways from it,

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.559
from this interview study that was done

00:15:09.559 --> 00:15:10.960
of people who do MLOps.

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:12.400
It's like a big difference

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:16.479
between what you might call regular software engineering

00:15:16.479 --> 00:15:18.359
and the process of MLOps,

00:15:18.359 --> 00:15:22.760
is that it is more iterative and interactive in nature.

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:25.760
And so you have to build tools for that kind of person,

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:28.359
for that kind of person, that kind of user persona.

00:15:28.359 --> 00:15:30.840
Another, just as a really concrete example,

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:32.159
if you have an app,

00:15:32.159 --> 00:15:34.080
like just a software app

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:37.000
that does not have machine learning in it,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.679
you, and someone talks about the performance of it,

00:15:40.679 --> 00:15:43.960
they're probably talking about things like latency,

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:45.320
how fast does the app run,

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:47.840
how much RAM does the app use?

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:50.479
But when you're talking about a machine learning app,

00:15:50.479 --> 00:15:53.200
an API that serves a model or something like that,

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:54.919
you do have to think about all those things.

00:15:54.919 --> 00:15:56.280
You have to think about latency,

00:15:56.280 --> 00:15:59.559
you have to think about how much memory it uses,

00:15:59.559 --> 00:16:01.200
how fast it returns predictions,

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:04.799
but you also have to think about performance

00:16:04.799 --> 00:16:08.440
in terms of the statistical characteristics of the model.

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:11.479
And because people who do machine learning,

00:16:11.479 --> 00:16:16.479
who do MLOps, have to think about both of those things,

00:16:16.479 --> 00:16:19.000
the tools that they need to use,

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.119
forefront those concerns,

00:16:21.119 --> 00:16:24.880
have to really, have to prioritize

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:26.880
that sort of whole universe

00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:28.479
of the things that people have to think about

00:16:28.479 --> 00:16:30.179
when it comes to machine learning.

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:34.599
It has been interesting to notice

00:16:34.599 --> 00:16:39.280
who has responded well to our tools that we've been building,

00:16:39.280 --> 00:16:41.479
who thinks it's a good fit.

00:16:41.479 --> 00:16:46.479
And it is usually people who have the data experience

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:52.239
and are needing to take their model the last mile.

00:16:52.239 --> 00:16:54.380
It's like they need to get it the last mile

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:56.679
so that it is useful to their organization.

00:16:56.679 --> 00:16:59.799
And that's the user we think of when we build this.

00:16:59.799 --> 00:17:04.160
Yeah, and you mentioned you read some surveys

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:07.119
to learn about user frustration,

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:10.439
and you also worked on survey data yourself

00:17:10.439 --> 00:17:11.959
while you were at Stack Overflow.

00:17:11.959 --> 00:17:14.800
I remember reading those surveys published

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:16.920
by Stack Overflow, it's very interesting

00:17:16.920 --> 00:17:20.780
to learn developers' habits and patterns.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:23.640
And when we think about survey data,

00:17:23.640 --> 00:17:26.439
it seems very simple, you just aggregate them.

00:17:26.439 --> 00:17:30.479
But we know you have data from different sources,

00:17:30.479 --> 00:17:31.880
the formats are different,

00:17:31.880 --> 00:17:34.400
you're dealing with missing data.

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:36.839
Can you tell us what are the challenges

00:17:37.560 --> 00:17:38.400
when you work with survey data,

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:40.920
and how do you get an interesting story

00:17:40.920 --> 00:17:42.839
that's also accurate?

00:17:42.839 --> 00:17:47.040
Yeah, it is, so working on the Stack Overflow

00:17:47.040 --> 00:17:52.040
developer survey was honestly quite stressful at the time,

00:17:54.140 --> 00:17:55.920
partly because it was fairly public.

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:56.839
It was fairly public.

00:17:56.839 --> 00:17:59.719
People would pay quite a bit of attention to it,

00:17:59.719 --> 00:18:01.680
and it was enormous.

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:03.880
On the years that I worked on the survey,

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:08.880
it would have on the order of 70,000 responses,

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:13.760
90,000 responses, and so it's an online opt-in survey.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:17.319
So in this way, it's different from surveys

00:18:17.319 --> 00:18:18.359
that you might hear about

00:18:18.359 --> 00:18:21.079
through a government statistical organizations,

00:18:21.079 --> 00:18:24.780
where they want a sample that is reflective

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:27.400
of the population of that country,

00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:30.160
and they work very hard so that the people

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:34.719
who take the survey are, they know how to map

00:18:34.719 --> 00:18:37.880
from the responses they get to the population.

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:41.319
Now, there's no census out there of developers.

00:18:41.319 --> 00:18:44.479
No one knows actually how many there are,

00:18:44.479 --> 00:18:48.400
or what their demographic characteristics are like,

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:51.479
and when you have an online opt-in survey,

00:18:51.479 --> 00:18:54.520
one of the aspects of it that I found most challenging

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:57.439
was how to accurately communicate

00:18:57.439 --> 00:18:59.560
about the nature of those results,

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:01.280
and this is something that Stack Overflow

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:03.920
got a fair amount of criticism for over the year,

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:05.599
and some of that I think was quite fair.

00:19:05.599 --> 00:19:08.920
So a big piece of this would be gender representation

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:10.000
in that survey.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.680
So I don't remember the exact numbers,

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:16.420
but you would see when I would work on that survey,

00:19:16.420 --> 00:19:19.079
the first year that I worked on that survey,

00:19:19.079 --> 00:19:22.260
it was 5% of the respondents

00:19:22.260 --> 00:19:25.079
were women and gender minorities, very low,

00:19:25.079 --> 00:19:28.319
and so when you would, if you are a woman in tech

00:19:28.319 --> 00:19:31.760
and you see that, you think, this is not representing me,

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:33.959
like this survey is not representing me.

00:19:33.959 --> 00:19:37.160
So one of my priorities when I worked on the survey,

00:19:37.160 --> 00:19:40.599
first of all, we invested in trying to

00:19:40.599 --> 00:19:43.239
increase that proportion.

00:19:43.239 --> 00:19:45.599
We would go to groups like PyLadies,

00:19:45.599 --> 00:19:47.599
we would go to groups that were,

00:19:47.599 --> 00:19:49.199
you would find women in tech and say,

00:19:49.199 --> 00:19:51.400
hey, can you share this with your members,

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:52.880
like in your Slack, so that,

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:55.199
because we want to hear, in this example,

00:19:55.199 --> 00:19:56.459
like we want to hear from women

00:19:56.459 --> 00:19:57.800
and gender minorities in tech,

00:19:58.280 --> 00:20:00.160
and we did, we bumped up the proportion,

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:04.000
like we doubled it, we doubled the proportion of respondents

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:05.359
but the thing is, we don't actually know

00:20:05.359 --> 00:20:07.400
what the real answer is, we don't actually know.

00:20:07.400 --> 00:20:10.079
You can, in the US, you can get some data

00:20:10.079 --> 00:20:13.359
from the Bureau of Labor Statistics to try to,

00:20:13.359 --> 00:20:16.599
but even that, like how they define a software engineer

00:20:16.599 --> 00:20:19.560
or a developer isn't actually like a perfect mapping

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:22.199
to probably have you and I understand what a,

00:20:22.199 --> 00:20:24.880
so it's actually kind of an open question.

00:20:24.880 --> 00:20:27.300
So the first piece is like data collection.

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:30.260
How can we responsibly collect data?

00:20:30.260 --> 00:20:31.900
How can we try to make sure we're hearing

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:33.339
from the important voices?

00:20:33.339 --> 00:20:36.140
And then the second piece, how do we analyze the data

00:20:36.140 --> 00:20:37.839
and how do we present the data?

00:20:37.839 --> 00:20:41.400
So one thing we found, or one thing I really prioritized

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:43.939
is that, I'm just gonna stick with this example,

00:20:43.939 --> 00:20:46.819
the gender example, although it applies in other ways

00:20:46.819 --> 00:20:48.579
as well, like other kind of characteristics

00:20:48.579 --> 00:20:50.640
of who people are, but I'm just, for this example,

00:20:50.640 --> 00:20:52.739
I'm gonna stick with the gender one.

00:20:52.739 --> 00:20:56.180
We would try to disaggregate results

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:59.699
and talk about differences and say, oh, okay,

00:20:59.699 --> 00:21:02.020
we see that some questions

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:05.000
on the Stack Overflow Developer Survey were about salary.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:08.780
So we're like, okay, can we talk about differences

00:21:08.780 --> 00:21:11.579
in reported salaries by gender?

00:21:11.579 --> 00:21:15.420
And is it the same for people who are backend developers

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:18.060
versus DevOps versus data scientists?

00:21:18.060 --> 00:21:19.660
Are there gender differences

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:22.540
across different experience levels?

00:21:22.540 --> 00:21:24.459
Like this was actually something we did find.

00:21:24.459 --> 00:21:26.939
Women who were early in their careers,

00:21:26.939 --> 00:21:30.219
we didn't see differences in salary.

00:21:30.219 --> 00:21:35.140
So like young women are earning the same as young men

00:21:35.140 --> 00:21:37.859
who are in tech, but if you looked at,

00:21:37.859 --> 00:21:40.140
that was not true for very experienced women.

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:43.060
So the most experienced women,

00:21:43.060 --> 00:21:46.219
like the women who are further in their careers, older,

00:21:46.219 --> 00:21:50.380
earned less than men with the same experience

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:51.619
and the same kind of role.

00:21:51.819 --> 00:21:55.060
If you were like in IT versus data scientists,

00:21:55.060 --> 00:21:55.900
you know this.

00:21:55.900 --> 00:21:57.260
So if you controlled for those things, you would see,

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:00.579
ah, we don't see a difference for early career people

00:22:00.579 --> 00:22:02.739
and we do see a difference for late career people.

00:22:02.739 --> 00:22:06.979
So I prioritized in the analysis

00:22:06.979 --> 00:22:09.500
trying to do the best we could

00:22:09.500 --> 00:22:13.020
given that we had an opt-in online survey,

00:22:13.020 --> 00:22:16.459
which is not representative of the population,

00:22:16.459 --> 00:22:17.699
partly because we didn't know.

00:22:17.699 --> 00:22:20.459
There was nowhere for us to go to get the right,

00:22:20.579 --> 00:22:21.699
what would we expect?

00:22:21.699 --> 00:22:22.859
What's the right proportion?

00:22:22.859 --> 00:22:23.739
We don't know.

00:22:23.739 --> 00:22:27.380
So we tried to prioritize understanding differences.

00:22:27.380 --> 00:22:28.939
Yeah, I think that makes sense.

00:22:28.939 --> 00:22:32.780
For example, I know there are definitely

00:22:32.780 --> 00:22:35.900
more male developers than female,

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:38.900
but you want to hear a female developer's voice,

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:41.939
but you also cannot just rebalance that to 50-50,

00:22:41.939 --> 00:22:44.619
then that's not a fair representation.

00:22:44.619 --> 00:22:47.540
Although as a woman, we want to make sure

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:48.420
our voice are heard.

00:22:48.420 --> 00:22:51.459
So yeah, I can see the challenges there.

00:22:51.459 --> 00:22:54.939
And I also like that when you break into the age group,

00:22:54.939 --> 00:22:56.900
you see the story.

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:57.739
Yeah.

00:22:57.739 --> 00:22:59.900
Yeah, so did you investigate,

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:02.819
have some assumptions on the reason behind it?

00:23:02.819 --> 00:23:05.339
So I think, I certainly talk to people about it.

00:23:05.339 --> 00:23:07.300
So some people when they hear that result,

00:23:07.300 --> 00:23:11.660
they think, great, there was a problem in the past,

00:23:11.660 --> 00:23:13.260
but we don't have that problem now.

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:14.099
That's what they say.

00:23:14.099 --> 00:23:15.459
That's some people when they hear that data,

00:23:15.459 --> 00:23:16.300
that's what they think.

00:23:16.540 --> 00:23:21.540
Okay, maybe 20 years ago, there was more unfairness in tech

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:23.099
and now we're okay.

00:23:23.099 --> 00:23:25.579
Now we're okay, like the people who are doing this.

00:23:25.579 --> 00:23:27.739
So that's one possible answer.

00:23:27.739 --> 00:23:31.619
Another possible reason that can contribute to this

00:23:31.619 --> 00:23:34.500
is that companies don't do a great job

00:23:34.500 --> 00:23:36.420
of supporting women in career growth,

00:23:36.420 --> 00:23:38.579
that women hit ceilings.

00:23:38.579 --> 00:23:40.819
And actually, I do see this happening,

00:23:40.819 --> 00:23:43.380
that women as they grow in their career,

00:23:43.420 --> 00:23:46.540
often get shunted to less technical roles,

00:23:46.540 --> 00:23:49.099
often get shunted to, oh, okay,

00:23:49.099 --> 00:23:51.699
I see that you're very good at talking to people.

00:23:51.699 --> 00:23:53.699
So let's put you in a management role.

00:23:53.699 --> 00:23:56.380
And if women, I think especially when women

00:23:56.380 --> 00:23:59.939
go to management roles too early in their career,

00:23:59.939 --> 00:24:03.020
it puts a ceiling on them because they are not perceived

00:24:03.020 --> 00:24:05.420
as having the technical credibility

00:24:05.420 --> 00:24:08.979
to be able to really grow a very long time in their career.

00:24:08.979 --> 00:24:12.699
So the data that we had could not answer why,

00:24:12.699 --> 00:24:14.500
but there are different ways to think about it.

00:24:14.500 --> 00:24:16.060
Of course, it might not just be one thing.

00:24:16.060 --> 00:24:17.140
It might be multiple things.

00:24:17.140 --> 00:24:21.859
Maybe the situation is better today than 20 years ago.

00:24:21.859 --> 00:24:26.859
And maybe also companies don't do a great job

00:24:27.339 --> 00:24:30.219
of retaining women and supporting women

00:24:30.219 --> 00:24:31.060
in their career growth.

00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:32.260
It can both be true.

00:24:32.260 --> 00:24:35.260
Yeah, what are some other interesting challenges

00:24:35.260 --> 00:24:37.140
when you worked on the survey data?

00:24:37.140 --> 00:24:39.619
So another interesting, more technical challenge,

00:24:39.619 --> 00:24:42.339
like less sort of people problem and more technical problem

00:24:42.979 --> 00:24:45.300
is that at the time at Stack Overflow,

00:24:45.300 --> 00:24:49.699
the data science ecosystem was all like R and Python.

00:24:49.699 --> 00:24:53.660
And at the time Stack Overflow had no Python,

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:55.939
no R in production anywhere.

00:24:55.939 --> 00:24:59.500
So I was doing the analysis with these data science tools,

00:24:59.500 --> 00:25:02.180
but we needed to get the results to production,

00:25:02.180 --> 00:25:03.459
to the website.

00:25:03.459 --> 00:25:05.819
And there was no way for me to use R,

00:25:05.819 --> 00:25:07.739
for me to use Python in that.

00:25:07.739 --> 00:25:10.579
So Stack Overflow is a pretty interesting website.

00:25:10.579 --> 00:25:14.459
It is super high performance, like really fast website

00:25:14.459 --> 00:25:16.219
that has been carefully built

00:25:16.219 --> 00:25:18.099
with these really fast technologies.

00:25:18.099 --> 00:25:19.780
So Python's too slow, R's too slow.

00:25:19.780 --> 00:25:20.819
It's not a good fit.

00:25:20.819 --> 00:25:24.219
What I found was the best way for me to be able

00:25:24.219 --> 00:25:28.619
to deliver those results was to deliver those results

00:25:28.619 --> 00:25:30.099
in an API.

00:25:30.099 --> 00:25:33.060
So in R, you can use Plumber, in Python,

00:25:33.060 --> 00:25:37.619
you can use FastAPI to deliver like results

00:25:37.619 --> 00:25:40.500
from a situation like a computer over here

00:25:41.380 --> 00:25:42.699
that has R or Python available.

00:25:42.699 --> 00:25:45.979
And then you can publish an API that another,

00:25:45.979 --> 00:25:49.780
like you might think of it as a survey microservice maybe.

00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:53.140
And then the like high performance website

00:25:53.140 --> 00:25:55.540
can slurp up the results when it needs to,

00:25:55.540 --> 00:25:59.459
update it on whatever time period is appropriate

00:25:59.459 --> 00:26:01.140
and get those results in.

00:26:01.140 --> 00:26:05.260
I did that actually with not only numbers,

00:26:05.260 --> 00:26:06.459
but also with plots.

00:26:06.459 --> 00:26:10.260
Like I would serve SVG plots in an API

00:26:11.020 --> 00:26:11.979
to get slurped up into the website.

00:26:11.979 --> 00:26:14.699
And so that was sometimes when people think

00:26:14.699 --> 00:26:18.300
about data science tools, like data science skills,

00:26:18.300 --> 00:26:20.060
you don't think as much about,

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:22.260
can I serve my results in an API?

00:26:22.260 --> 00:26:26.939
But that is, I feel like someone who has like the data chops

00:26:26.939 --> 00:26:29.739
and then also is able to really back that up

00:26:29.739 --> 00:26:32.939
with some level of engineering chop.

00:26:32.939 --> 00:26:34.699
Sure, I can publish an API for you.

00:26:34.699 --> 00:26:35.739
Like, where do you want it?

00:26:35.739 --> 00:26:39.579
That is something that the survey particularly showed me

00:26:39.619 --> 00:26:43.540
how much that can scale your impact in an organization.

00:26:43.540 --> 00:26:46.500
Yeah, especially if you work for a startup,

00:26:46.500 --> 00:26:49.579
you don't have a full engineering team to support you.

00:26:49.579 --> 00:26:52.979
So if you can't get your results out by yourself,

00:26:52.979 --> 00:26:55.819
then nobody can see it, nobody can use it.

00:26:55.819 --> 00:26:59.260
So having that engineering skill is mostly,

00:26:59.260 --> 00:27:02.339
I don't think you have to have every piece

00:27:02.339 --> 00:27:04.380
of engineering skill map exactly

00:27:04.380 --> 00:27:06.339
to the software engineer skill set,

00:27:06.339 --> 00:27:08.939
but I would call it kind of like on demand.

00:27:08.939 --> 00:27:11.020
What do you think about engineering skills

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:13.099
for data scientists?

00:27:13.099 --> 00:27:17.020
So I think that there are some that are table stakes,

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:19.540
table stakes, and I think those are things like

00:27:19.540 --> 00:27:23.780
in your language of choice, being very skilled

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:28.780
and effective at managing the nitty gritty of installation

00:27:29.420 --> 00:27:32.180
that you are someone who can build,

00:27:32.180 --> 00:27:35.780
that you are someone that effectively manages

00:27:35.780 --> 00:27:38.380
the software dependencies of your project.

00:27:38.380 --> 00:27:40.099
Maybe that seems even like a funny thing to say,

00:27:40.099 --> 00:27:43.219
but I run into people who really struggle with this piece,

00:27:43.219 --> 00:27:45.180
who really struggle with understanding

00:27:45.180 --> 00:27:47.099
like dependency management of projects

00:27:47.099 --> 00:27:48.540
and how to manage that.

00:27:48.540 --> 00:27:51.699
And it is a whole skill, like it is a whole skill.

00:27:51.699 --> 00:27:53.859
So that one I think is like table stakes,

00:27:53.859 --> 00:27:57.380
being able to be competent and get, right?

00:27:57.380 --> 00:27:58.979
Like that's table stakes.

00:27:58.979 --> 00:28:01.500
Then I think the things that will really,

00:28:01.500 --> 00:28:04.420
like if you can learn some combination of these

00:28:04.420 --> 00:28:06.420
to really push you forward,

00:28:06.459 --> 00:28:08.140
I think one of them is being someone

00:28:08.140 --> 00:28:10.380
who not only can manage dependencies,

00:28:10.380 --> 00:28:12.540
but who has packaging skill.

00:28:12.540 --> 00:28:16.339
So you can build a Python package,

00:28:16.339 --> 00:28:20.099
you can build an R package to package up code

00:28:20.099 --> 00:28:21.579
and be able to run it somewhere else

00:28:21.579 --> 00:28:23.099
so that you can then install it.

00:28:23.099 --> 00:28:25.219
So that, so not only can you manage it,

00:28:25.219 --> 00:28:26.939
but you can be the creator of it.

00:28:26.939 --> 00:28:30.420
So you are someone who understands REST APIs,

00:28:30.420 --> 00:28:31.459
like I just mentioned,

00:28:31.459 --> 00:28:33.819
like that's another really big piece.

00:28:33.819 --> 00:28:36.939
You are someone who maybe has some of the DevOps skills,

00:28:36.939 --> 00:28:39.540
like you understand Docker

00:28:39.540 --> 00:28:42.060
and when is appropriate to use Docker and how to use that.

00:28:42.060 --> 00:28:46.660
So these are skills that are not specifically about data,

00:28:46.660 --> 00:28:47.500
right?

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:49.260
They're not specifically about statistics

00:28:49.260 --> 00:28:51.060
or machine learning or data analysis,

00:28:51.060 --> 00:28:54.579
but they're about how do you operationalize

00:28:54.579 --> 00:28:56.219
the data analysis that you're doing.

00:28:56.219 --> 00:28:59.219
And previously you were in data science

00:28:59.219 --> 00:29:01.540
and now you're an engineering manager

00:29:01.540 --> 00:29:03.619
and you talked about you like the type of roles

00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:06.540
when you can dabble a little bit of both.

00:29:06.540 --> 00:29:10.939
So which persona do you identify with more,

00:29:10.939 --> 00:29:14.380
the data storyteller or the tool builder?

00:29:14.380 --> 00:29:17.060
Oh, that's a really tough question for me.

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:20.060
I, that's a very interesting question

00:29:20.060 --> 00:29:24.339
because my day job pays me for the tool builder piece.

00:29:24.339 --> 00:29:28.219
Like that is what my primary professional,

00:29:28.219 --> 00:29:29.459
and that's what I'm paid for, I guess.

00:29:29.459 --> 00:29:30.819
That's what's in my job description

00:29:30.819 --> 00:29:32.739
is the tool builder piece.

00:29:32.739 --> 00:29:37.140
But I think that my primary,

00:29:37.140 --> 00:29:41.619
how I think about myself is still on the practitioner side,

00:29:41.619 --> 00:29:46.500
is still, oh, I'm someone who does data science.

00:29:46.500 --> 00:29:48.500
Like you introduced me as like data scientist

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:49.339
and engineering manager,

00:29:49.339 --> 00:29:51.300
but I'm actually not a data scientist at my company.

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:53.939
Like we have data scientists and I'm not one of them.

00:29:53.939 --> 00:29:54.780
Like I am-

00:29:54.780 --> 00:29:56.819
But isn't your soul, you identify with it.

00:29:56.819 --> 00:29:58.260
I do, no, I think that's true.

00:29:58.260 --> 00:30:02.500
And I think it affects how I decide to build tools.

00:30:03.180 --> 00:30:05.540
I think the fact that that is my primary identity

00:30:05.540 --> 00:30:09.619
really informs the kinds of tools I wanna build,

00:30:09.619 --> 00:30:11.260
what I care about those tools,

00:30:11.260 --> 00:30:13.699
how much I care about documentation

00:30:13.699 --> 00:30:16.140
and communicating about those tools effectively.

00:30:16.140 --> 00:30:18.819
So that is a super tough question,

00:30:18.819 --> 00:30:21.819
but I think that it is most honest to say

00:30:21.819 --> 00:30:25.979
that I, my primary professional identity

00:30:25.979 --> 00:30:28.260
is still on the practitioner side.

00:30:28.260 --> 00:30:31.619
Yeah, and you're still maintaining your blog.

00:30:31.619 --> 00:30:33.979
Yeah, I read your blog.

00:30:33.979 --> 00:30:38.140
You tell a great story by interesting visualizations.

00:30:38.140 --> 00:30:40.819
And I know you like literature.

00:30:40.819 --> 00:30:43.260
You're passionate about tax analysis.

00:30:43.260 --> 00:30:47.380
Can you share a few interesting stories from your blog?

00:30:47.380 --> 00:30:49.579
Sure, I do.

00:30:49.579 --> 00:30:53.540
I always want to spend more time on my blog than I do,

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:57.339
but it has been very valuable to maintain it, to keep it

00:30:57.339 --> 00:31:00.420
and to continue to invest in it as I'm able,

00:31:00.420 --> 00:31:04.660
partly because I do love that really applied practice side.

00:31:04.660 --> 00:31:05.500
And you're right.

00:31:05.500 --> 00:31:08.339
One of the things that I love the most is text as data.

00:31:08.339 --> 00:31:11.660
It's interesting in the era of LLMs

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:15.099
to have so much more of the data science ecosystem

00:31:15.099 --> 00:31:16.780
thinking about text as data,

00:31:16.780 --> 00:31:21.300
but I love analyzing text,

00:31:21.300 --> 00:31:25.500
both from the very exploratory data analysis stage

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:27.180
through to training models.

00:31:27.180 --> 00:31:31.619
And I am interested in how these largest, biggest models

00:31:31.619 --> 00:31:33.459
are being trained and used.

00:31:33.459 --> 00:31:35.619
I will say, though, I spend most of my time

00:31:35.619 --> 00:31:38.619
a little bit lower in the hierarchy,

00:31:38.619 --> 00:31:43.060
like a little bit more towards exploratory work,

00:31:43.060 --> 00:31:47.380
visualization, and not those hard to interpret

00:31:47.380 --> 00:31:51.500
giant bot models, but models that are more transparent,

00:31:51.500 --> 00:31:54.579
that are more easy to interpret and know what they mean.

00:31:54.579 --> 00:31:59.260
One of my recent blog posts was about Taylor Swift's lyrics.

00:31:59.260 --> 00:32:03.819
And so treating the lyrics of Taylor Swift as a text data set

00:32:03.819 --> 00:32:06.540
and it builds model with that data.

00:32:06.540 --> 00:32:09.300
And so the particular model is an unsupervised model

00:32:09.300 --> 00:32:10.660
called a topic model.

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:15.660
And so topic models treat documents as mixtures of topics

00:32:15.979 --> 00:32:18.540
and each topic is a mixture of words.

00:32:18.540 --> 00:32:22.300
And it is, I feel like it's a really underrated tool

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:24.939
for when you have a corpus of language,

00:32:24.939 --> 00:32:26.619
open-ended survey questions.

00:32:26.619 --> 00:32:28.300
There are many ways you can apply this,

00:32:28.300 --> 00:32:30.579
but in this like fun example,

00:32:30.579 --> 00:32:32.500
I looked at the lyrics of Taylor Swift

00:32:32.500 --> 00:32:34.219
and looked to see,

00:32:34.219 --> 00:32:37.339
so treated the different songs as different documents

00:32:37.339 --> 00:32:38.619
and then tried to understand

00:32:38.619 --> 00:32:40.339
how are these related to each other?

00:32:40.339 --> 00:32:42.339
And if I remember correctly,

00:32:42.339 --> 00:32:45.500
like some of these results were like that the early albums

00:32:45.500 --> 00:32:47.619
of Taylor Swift have a lot in common

00:32:47.619 --> 00:32:49.780
in terms of the lyric content.

00:32:49.780 --> 00:32:51.180
If you look at the words that are there,

00:32:51.339 --> 00:32:52.699
like words about romance.

00:32:52.699 --> 00:32:56.699
And then if you look, reputation is really unique.

00:32:56.699 --> 00:33:00.660
It is lyrically unique compared to her other works,

00:33:00.660 --> 00:33:01.540
which makes sense.

00:33:01.540 --> 00:33:05.579
And then like Folklore and Evermore have a lot in common.

00:33:05.579 --> 00:33:08.020
They're like two of the albums that are the closest

00:33:08.020 --> 00:33:09.540
in terms of their lyric content,

00:33:09.540 --> 00:33:11.380
which definitely also makes sense.

00:33:11.380 --> 00:33:13.380
Those are albums that have a lot in common.

00:33:13.380 --> 00:33:14.939
So I love that as an example.

00:33:14.939 --> 00:33:17.579
I mean, those techniques can be applied

00:33:17.579 --> 00:33:21.260
in maybe more mundane or common ways,

00:33:21.260 --> 00:33:22.819
but it's really fun to look at something

00:33:22.819 --> 00:33:25.459
like Taylor Swift lyrics and do that.

00:33:25.459 --> 00:33:28.579
I actually did that the week after I went to see the movie.

00:33:28.579 --> 00:33:30.380
I went to see the concert film

00:33:30.380 --> 00:33:34.260
and it was like a little fun Taylor Swift moment for me.

00:33:34.260 --> 00:33:35.099
Yeah, that's great.

00:33:35.099 --> 00:33:36.819
I think a lot of people don't know

00:33:36.819 --> 00:33:38.660
what kind of project they should start with.

00:33:38.660 --> 00:33:40.900
You can just pick something that interests you.

00:33:40.900 --> 00:33:41.739
Yeah, absolutely.

00:33:41.739 --> 00:33:43.819
And I think actually the most fun part

00:33:43.819 --> 00:33:46.380
lies in the exploratory analysis.

00:33:46.380 --> 00:33:48.579
There are a lot of low-hanging fruits.

00:33:48.579 --> 00:33:50.180
And if you want to get started

00:33:50.180 --> 00:33:53.420
on your public portfolio projects,

00:33:53.420 --> 00:33:56.660
you don't have to go into the very complicated

00:33:56.660 --> 00:33:57.699
machine learning model.

00:33:57.699 --> 00:34:01.900
Start with something, exploratory analysis, analyzing,

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:04.300
I don't know, your favorite food or some,

00:34:04.300 --> 00:34:08.179
I think there's public data about Yelp stars

00:34:08.179 --> 00:34:09.219
and things like that.

00:34:09.219 --> 00:34:10.699
And to add onto that,

00:34:10.699 --> 00:34:13.500
I think it is that actually

00:34:13.500 --> 00:34:15.939
those are incredibly valuable skills.

00:34:16.500 --> 00:34:21.500
If you're someone who's very quick and good at EDA,

00:34:21.540 --> 00:34:23.459
like those people are incredible.

00:34:23.459 --> 00:34:25.620
Like those people are very impactful

00:34:25.620 --> 00:34:28.060
in the organizations where they are, for sure.

00:34:28.060 --> 00:34:31.300
Because especially when it comes to analytics,

00:34:31.300 --> 00:34:34.419
the leaders need the insight fast.

00:34:34.419 --> 00:34:36.979
Being quick, being familiar with the tools

00:34:36.979 --> 00:34:41.100
and also sometimes you do need to put on like investigator

00:34:41.100 --> 00:34:45.020
hat to evaluate the definition of things.

00:34:45.020 --> 00:34:46.060
Those are important.

00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:50.139
So how did you hone your skill set?

00:34:50.139 --> 00:34:53.659
How do you develop your skills in doing EDAs?

00:34:53.659 --> 00:34:55.459
Yeah, this is a very interesting question

00:34:55.459 --> 00:34:58.739
because it is exploratory in nature.

00:34:58.739 --> 00:35:01.620
It is kind of hard to say,

00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:03.659
what is the right thing to do?

00:35:03.659 --> 00:35:05.780
And when do you know you've done a good job?

00:35:05.780 --> 00:35:07.659
And when do you know you're done?

00:35:07.659 --> 00:35:08.699
When do you know you're done?

00:35:08.699 --> 00:35:09.699
It will never be done.

00:35:09.699 --> 00:35:11.260
You always have another question.

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:12.979
Yeah, so one of my favorite books

00:35:13.020 --> 00:35:16.300
that kind of approaches the process of this

00:35:16.300 --> 00:35:17.820
is an R-specific book,

00:35:17.820 --> 00:35:21.219
but I think that it, at least those first couple chapters

00:35:21.219 --> 00:35:22.939
would really benefit anyone,

00:35:22.939 --> 00:35:25.459
even if they use Python or another Julia

00:35:25.459 --> 00:35:26.580
or another language.

00:35:26.580 --> 00:35:28.620
So the book is called R for Data Science.

00:35:28.620 --> 00:35:30.219
It's by Hadley Wickham.

00:35:30.219 --> 00:35:32.659
And it is the first couple chapters

00:35:32.659 --> 00:35:35.820
talk about the iterative nature of say,

00:35:35.820 --> 00:35:38.739
you read data and you import data

00:35:38.739 --> 00:35:41.459
and then you do this process of visualize,

00:35:41.459 --> 00:35:43.860
summarize, model.

00:35:43.860 --> 00:35:48.179
And this process tends to loop back on itself

00:35:48.179 --> 00:35:49.659
multiple times where then,

00:35:49.659 --> 00:35:52.860
oh, I saw, oh, I see this result.

00:35:52.860 --> 00:35:54.659
Let me go and make another plot.

00:35:54.659 --> 00:35:56.379
Let me do another summarization.

00:35:56.379 --> 00:35:58.979
Let me build another maybe like simple model

00:35:58.979 --> 00:36:03.340
to learn what I need to, what I can about this data set.

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:08.340
And it is a matter of judgment and kind of taste.

00:36:08.500 --> 00:36:09.820
Like when you're done

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:12.300
and when it's time to say communicate,

00:36:12.300 --> 00:36:15.100
when it's time to then say, okay, stakeholder,

00:36:15.100 --> 00:36:16.659
here is this result here.

00:36:16.659 --> 00:36:19.139
So I think what has helped me

00:36:19.139 --> 00:36:22.500
kind of develop instincts around that

00:36:22.500 --> 00:36:26.020
is knowing like being able to look at

00:36:26.020 --> 00:36:29.219
how people respond to what I give them

00:36:29.219 --> 00:36:33.659
and also to be sensitive to where people are coming from.

00:36:33.659 --> 00:36:36.139
Are we in a situation where someone wants

00:36:36.139 --> 00:36:38.580
like a ton of detail?

00:36:38.659 --> 00:36:39.899
Like they wanna see a lot

00:36:39.899 --> 00:36:41.979
or are we in a situation where someone wants

00:36:41.979 --> 00:36:45.780
some like top line TLDR kind of situation

00:36:45.780 --> 00:36:47.500
about what some results are.

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:50.979
So I think practice, I think acknowledging

00:36:50.979 --> 00:36:52.939
that you do have to use your judgment

00:36:52.939 --> 00:36:56.020
in knowing when you're done, when something is done.

00:36:56.020 --> 00:36:58.899
And I think experience of seeing

00:36:58.899 --> 00:37:01.860
what has landed really well with people

00:37:01.860 --> 00:37:04.780
and when did people either want more or less.

00:37:04.820 --> 00:37:05.659
Yeah.

00:37:05.659 --> 00:37:08.860
For example, when you used to present your analysis

00:37:08.860 --> 00:37:13.379
to a leadership, do you have a process?

00:37:13.379 --> 00:37:15.540
Did you have your favorite toolkits?

00:37:15.540 --> 00:37:20.540
Yeah, I was a huge user of R Markdown at the time.

00:37:22.260 --> 00:37:24.500
And so what I would use today would be Quarto.

00:37:24.500 --> 00:37:27.620
So Quarto is like sort of a next generation iteration

00:37:27.620 --> 00:37:28.939
of what R Markdown is.

00:37:28.939 --> 00:37:33.820
And Quarto works for Python, R, Observable, like Julia.

00:37:33.820 --> 00:37:37.500
For that, I feel like what the superpower that gave me

00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:42.500
was the ability to quickly generate reproducible reports.

00:37:45.179 --> 00:37:48.659
And so I would do things like write in

00:37:48.659 --> 00:37:51.060
like what would be like a Quarto doc now.

00:37:51.060 --> 00:37:54.379
So text code, making the plots, making the results.

00:37:54.379 --> 00:37:55.939
And then I would run the whole thing,

00:37:55.939 --> 00:38:00.260
render the whole thing to either a PDF or Google Docs.

00:38:00.260 --> 00:38:03.179
Or if I was doing a presentation, I would make slides

00:38:03.179 --> 00:38:05.139
and I could do it reproducibly.

00:38:05.139 --> 00:38:08.219
I never had to do, like the superpower it gave me

00:38:08.219 --> 00:38:11.020
is that I was never like copying and pasting stuff

00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:13.060
or showing someone outdated results.

00:38:13.060 --> 00:38:16.060
Like I had really reproducible practices.

00:38:16.060 --> 00:38:17.860
The other thing that was like a tool

00:38:17.860 --> 00:38:21.500
that was like a superpower for me was Shiny.

00:38:21.500 --> 00:38:25.179
So Shiny is a tool for making interactive apps

00:38:25.179 --> 00:38:27.100
for Python and for R.

00:38:27.100 --> 00:38:29.260
Being someone who knew how to use Shiny,

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:33.899
let me make, picture a interactive data app

00:38:33.899 --> 00:38:36.620
that a stakeholder could then come and they could-

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:37.459
Drag and drop.

00:38:37.459 --> 00:38:38.300
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:38:38.300 --> 00:38:39.939
Shiny made me so effective.

00:38:39.939 --> 00:38:41.419
Shiny made me so effective.

00:38:41.419 --> 00:38:44.139
And it's funny, at the time I was not,

00:38:44.139 --> 00:38:46.340
like I did not work for my company now,

00:38:46.340 --> 00:38:48.739
but part of the reason I wanted to come to my company

00:38:48.739 --> 00:38:50.899
is because it was the company that made these tools.

00:38:50.899 --> 00:38:53.860
So I don't personally work on Quarto or Shiny,

00:38:53.860 --> 00:38:55.580
like I work on Bedivere, like I said,

00:38:55.580 --> 00:38:57.739
but I know coming from me now,

00:38:57.739 --> 00:38:58.699
it's sure you're gonna say that,

00:38:58.699 --> 00:39:01.060
but literally those were like my superpowers

00:39:01.060 --> 00:39:02.899
when I was a data science practitioner.

00:39:02.899 --> 00:39:05.500
Like being able to generate reproducible reports

00:39:05.500 --> 00:39:08.020
really quickly, being able to make interactive apps

00:39:08.020 --> 00:39:11.060
really quickly, like it made people view me

00:39:11.060 --> 00:39:14.979
as incredibly productive and helpful to the org.

00:39:14.979 --> 00:39:15.899
Yeah.

00:39:15.899 --> 00:39:20.060
And you mentioned now Posit supports both Python

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:24.419
and R packages and here's comes the hot topic.

00:39:24.419 --> 00:39:25.260
Okay.

00:39:25.260 --> 00:39:27.260
Python or R, which one should you use?

00:39:27.379 --> 00:39:30.459
Especially I think now with the MMOps,

00:39:30.459 --> 00:39:33.060
I don't think a lot of people use R.

00:39:33.060 --> 00:39:34.620
So what's your take on that?

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:38.540
Yeah, so I think that the right answer

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:41.459
is the one that you are more productive in.

00:39:41.459 --> 00:39:46.060
If you are someone who is more productive in Python,

00:39:46.060 --> 00:39:47.939
then that is the right tool for you.

00:39:47.939 --> 00:39:49.739
And if you are someone,

00:39:49.739 --> 00:39:52.739
I think it depends on your own skills

00:39:52.739 --> 00:39:54.340
and what is a better fit for you.

00:39:54.340 --> 00:39:58.379
I do also think that sometimes the tooling is better

00:39:58.379 --> 00:39:59.620
in one than the other.

00:39:59.620 --> 00:40:03.139
Like a real strength of R is that every kind

00:40:03.139 --> 00:40:05.179
of statistical model that exists,

00:40:05.179 --> 00:40:07.100
there's an R package for that.

00:40:07.100 --> 00:40:09.300
And so if you have needs around,

00:40:09.300 --> 00:40:12.699
say like specific statistical needs

00:40:12.699 --> 00:40:14.500
around the kind of models that you build,

00:40:14.500 --> 00:40:17.419
or like often R is used a lot in situations

00:40:17.419 --> 00:40:20.820
where you have fairly sophisticated statistical needs.

00:40:20.820 --> 00:40:22.540
You can't just like brute force something.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:23.780
Like you need to be quite careful.

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:26.540
That's why it's used a lot in clinical trials,

00:40:26.540 --> 00:40:28.500
why it's used a lot in like human,

00:40:28.500 --> 00:40:30.580
like research with like people,

00:40:30.580 --> 00:40:32.979
because you're looking for like subtle effects

00:40:32.979 --> 00:40:36.739
and you need to make sure your stats are rock solid.

00:40:36.739 --> 00:40:38.659
And so if you are in that situation,

00:40:38.659 --> 00:40:39.699
you might want to consider,

00:40:39.699 --> 00:40:42.580
hey, can I make sure that this will work well?

00:40:42.580 --> 00:40:44.780
That I can use R in a way that is good.

00:40:44.780 --> 00:40:48.939
There are, of course, amazing tools in Python as well.

00:40:48.939 --> 00:40:51.780
I think one that I often will turn to Python for,

00:40:52.020 --> 00:40:53.979
just as an example, is spaCy.

00:40:53.979 --> 00:40:57.580
spaCy is a, like we talked about, I love text data.

00:40:57.580 --> 00:41:00.179
spaCy is a project and package

00:41:00.179 --> 00:41:03.699
for natural language processing in Python that is amazing.

00:41:03.699 --> 00:41:05.139
Like it's amazing, I love it.

00:41:05.139 --> 00:41:07.459
The people who built it did such a good job.

00:41:07.459 --> 00:41:08.500
I'm such a fan.

00:41:08.500 --> 00:41:10.219
And it is just for Python.

00:41:10.219 --> 00:41:12.699
And so that is something that I would turn to Python for

00:41:12.699 --> 00:41:13.659
to use the tool.

00:41:13.659 --> 00:41:17.620
So I think the two things to think about are,

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:18.939
which one are you better at?

00:41:18.939 --> 00:41:23.939
So for example, I am just way better with the tidyverse

00:41:24.060 --> 00:41:26.899
than I am with like pandas or pollers or any,

00:41:26.899 --> 00:41:28.179
like I'm just way faster.

00:41:28.179 --> 00:41:29.659
I'm just way faster.

00:41:29.659 --> 00:41:31.300
It matches how my brain thinks.

00:41:31.300 --> 00:41:35.419
And so if I need to do data munging, data EDA,

00:41:35.419 --> 00:41:38.060
if I need to do EDA, I'm gonna use the tidyverse

00:41:38.060 --> 00:41:40.459
because I'm so effective with it.

00:41:40.459 --> 00:41:41.780
So there's one piece that's like,

00:41:41.780 --> 00:41:43.300
what are you effective with?

00:41:43.300 --> 00:41:44.139
Use that.

00:41:44.139 --> 00:41:45.820
And then there's the other piece of

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:50.179
the specific task you're doing, where are the best tools?

00:41:50.179 --> 00:41:51.620
Where are the best tools?

00:41:51.620 --> 00:41:54.300
And I will find myself picking up different tools

00:41:54.300 --> 00:41:57.179
depending on what it is that I want to do.

00:41:57.179 --> 00:41:59.939
I do think people will,

00:41:59.939 --> 00:42:02.580
depending on companies and organizations,

00:42:02.580 --> 00:42:05.540
sometimes we'll get really locked in to one,

00:42:05.540 --> 00:42:07.219
like we are an all Python shop.

00:42:07.219 --> 00:42:09.459
We are an all R kind of shop.

00:42:09.459 --> 00:42:12.699
And so sometimes that also is part of the reality

00:42:12.699 --> 00:42:15.260
that like, oh, at this company,

00:42:15.260 --> 00:42:17.580
they've made a decision that all of our data science

00:42:17.580 --> 00:42:19.020
needs to be in Python.

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:22.739
And so that's also sometimes a constraint that comes in

00:42:22.739 --> 00:42:24.500
is like where you are working,

00:42:24.500 --> 00:42:26.219
maybe you don't have complete freedom

00:42:26.219 --> 00:42:29.179
to decide what tool you are going to use.

00:42:29.179 --> 00:42:32.219
So one of the things I'm really been happy about,

00:42:32.219 --> 00:42:37.179
I feel like lately is people acknowledging more

00:42:37.179 --> 00:42:39.459
these kinds of realities and not,

00:42:39.459 --> 00:42:43.699
I am not someone who is interested

00:42:43.699 --> 00:42:46.860
or willing to engage in one is good and one is bad.

00:42:46.860 --> 00:42:47.699
They're different.

00:42:47.699 --> 00:42:49.739
The trade-offs are different.

00:42:49.739 --> 00:42:52.739
And there are other really interesting projects out there too

00:42:52.739 --> 00:42:56.020
which we may all be wanting to use in five years.

00:42:56.020 --> 00:42:59.179
Julia hasn't, like some people who use Julia,

00:42:59.179 --> 00:43:00.300
love Julia, right?

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:01.580
There's really cool stuff out there.

00:43:01.580 --> 00:43:04.340
It's been really interesting to see Mojo come out recently,

00:43:04.340 --> 00:43:06.699
this like new, really fast kind of language.

00:43:06.699 --> 00:43:11.699
So I think it's, I am very professionally associated with R

00:43:12.100 --> 00:43:15.899
but it is for sure not the only language I use.

00:43:15.899 --> 00:43:18.540
And I think that it's good not to get,

00:43:18.540 --> 00:43:20.179
I think it's good to realize

00:43:20.179 --> 00:43:22.300
once you have learned one programming language

00:43:22.300 --> 00:43:24.300
is not that hard to learn another one.

00:43:24.300 --> 00:43:27.620
The things that are the hardest are the,

00:43:27.620 --> 00:43:29.260
at least this is my opinion,

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:30.860
the things that are the hardest moving

00:43:30.860 --> 00:43:32.939
when you enter into a different language

00:43:32.939 --> 00:43:34.379
is usually not the syntax.

00:43:34.379 --> 00:43:37.060
It is usually what is that language's

00:43:37.060 --> 00:43:39.060
packaging ecosystem like?

00:43:39.060 --> 00:43:39.899
Yeah.

00:43:39.899 --> 00:43:41.580
And how is it different than the one you're used to?

00:43:41.580 --> 00:43:43.419
So I feel like that's the hardest piece usually

00:43:43.419 --> 00:43:44.780
is like wrapping your mind

00:43:44.780 --> 00:43:47.500
around a different set of constraints

00:43:47.500 --> 00:43:50.419
in terms of how packages are distributed

00:43:50.419 --> 00:43:51.780
and dependencies are managed.

00:43:51.780 --> 00:43:52.899
Yeah, I think that's a great point.

00:43:52.899 --> 00:43:54.939
A lot of times we're trapped in the grammar

00:43:54.939 --> 00:43:59.020
or how does Python count from zero and R from one?

00:43:59.020 --> 00:44:02.540
But it's a bigger problem, the ecosystem.

00:44:02.540 --> 00:44:06.020
And also I think another great point you brought up is

00:44:06.020 --> 00:44:08.139
you don't have to abandon the language

00:44:08.139 --> 00:44:09.260
you're most familiar with

00:44:09.260 --> 00:44:11.939
just because another language gets more popular.

00:44:11.939 --> 00:44:14.659
I think it does help you to be more productive,

00:44:14.659 --> 00:44:16.300
more collaborative with our team

00:44:16.300 --> 00:44:18.979
if you learn more popular language,

00:44:18.979 --> 00:44:21.300
in this case, maybe Python.

00:44:21.300 --> 00:44:22.860
But if R is your strength,

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:26.060
you still can use it, do some quick analysis.

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:27.379
And like you mentioned,

00:44:27.379 --> 00:44:30.620
I know for example, time series, causal inference,

00:44:30.620 --> 00:44:32.060
there are more packages in R.

00:44:32.899 --> 00:44:35.459
Yeah, those are other areas where it has its strengths

00:44:35.459 --> 00:44:36.300
as well.

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:38.540
Yeah, so before we wrap up,

00:44:38.540 --> 00:44:40.580
what are something you're excited about

00:44:40.580 --> 00:44:43.780
in your career or personal life this year?

00:44:43.780 --> 00:44:45.179
Oh yeah, that's a great question.

00:44:45.179 --> 00:44:46.659
One thing in my professional life

00:44:46.659 --> 00:44:48.419
I'm really excited about this year

00:44:48.419 --> 00:44:50.739
is that I'm keynoting at SciPy.

00:44:50.739 --> 00:44:51.580
Oh wow.

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:54.379
Yeah, so this July I'm giving a keynote at SciPy

00:44:54.379 --> 00:44:57.500
and it is one of the themes at SciPy this year

00:44:57.500 --> 00:45:01.899
is scientific computing across different languages.

00:45:01.899 --> 00:45:04.300
And so I'm really excited to get to go

00:45:04.300 --> 00:45:07.060
and talk about like my own experiences

00:45:07.060 --> 00:45:10.300
building projects across different languages.

00:45:10.300 --> 00:45:11.899
And what are things,

00:45:11.899 --> 00:45:13.739
they're less about a specific language

00:45:13.739 --> 00:45:16.620
and more about scientific computing generally.

00:45:16.620 --> 00:45:18.020
And then what are the things that come up

00:45:18.020 --> 00:45:18.860
that are different?

00:45:18.860 --> 00:45:21.219
Like when you're working with a Python user,

00:45:21.219 --> 00:45:22.939
when you're working with an R user,

00:45:22.939 --> 00:45:25.379
what are the things that actually do have to be different?

00:45:25.379 --> 00:45:28.100
So I'm super excited about giving that keynote.

00:45:28.100 --> 00:45:30.219
I'm super honored that they asked me.

00:45:30.219 --> 00:45:31.540
So that is one thing.

00:45:31.540 --> 00:45:33.219
And then I guess another thing,

00:45:33.219 --> 00:45:35.060
this is also conference related.

00:45:35.060 --> 00:45:38.580
So my company is having its conference in August

00:45:38.580 --> 00:45:41.620
and I'm helping me and one of the people on my team,

00:45:41.620 --> 00:45:45.219
Isabel, is our teaching a workshop on using Vetiver.

00:45:45.219 --> 00:45:47.739
So it'll be the second time we've taught this workshop.

00:45:47.739 --> 00:45:51.979
And it's so fun to sit down with people in a room

00:45:51.979 --> 00:45:53.820
and help them get from a place

00:45:53.820 --> 00:45:56.020
where they have not done something before,

00:45:56.020 --> 00:45:57.260
like deployed a model

00:45:57.260 --> 00:45:59.219
and get them to that first deployment.

00:45:59.219 --> 00:46:00.500
It's just really exciting.

00:46:00.500 --> 00:46:01.699
So I'm looking forward to that as well.

00:46:01.699 --> 00:46:02.659
Yeah, that's awesome.

00:46:02.659 --> 00:46:04.060
Looking forward as well.

00:46:04.060 --> 00:46:06.979
Thank you, Julia, for coming to the show today.

00:46:06.979 --> 00:46:08.100
Thank you so much for having me.

00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:09.860
It was a pleasure to chat with you.

